node.Title: DBMS Selection
node.Description: (Main Model)

node.Title: Functional appropriateness
node.Description: degree to which the functions facilitate the accomplishment of specified tasks and objectives

node.Title: Functional completeness
node.Description: degree to which the set of functions covers all the specified tasks and user objectives

node.Title: Functional correctness
node.Description: degree to which a product or system provides the correct results with the needed degree of precision

node.Title: Functional suitability
node.Description: degree to which a product or system provides functions that meet stated and implied needs when used under specified conditions

node.Title: Reliability
node.Description: degree to which a system, product or component performs specified functions under specified conditions for a specified period

node.Title: Performance efficiency
node.Description: performance relative to the amount of resources used under stated conditions

node.Title: Usability
node.Description: degree to which a product or system can be used by specified users to achieve specified goals with effectiveness, efficiency and satisfaction in a specified context of use

node.Title: Maintainability
node.Description: degree of effectiveness and efficiency with which a product or system can be modified by the intended maintainers

node.Title: Security
node.Description: degree to which a product or system protects information and data so that persons or other products or systems have the degree of data access appropriate to their types and levels of authorization

node.Title: Compatibility
node.Description: degree to which a product, system or component can exchange information with other products, systems or components, and/or perform its required functions, while sharing the same hardware or software environment

node.Title: Portability
node.Description: degree of effectiveness and efficiency with which a system, product or component can be transferred from one hardware, software or other operational or usage environment to another

node.Title: Supplier
node.Description: Description about anyone who provides goods or services to a company or individuals.

node.Title: Cost
node.Description: Denotes the amount of money that a company spends on the creation or production of goods or services.

node.Title: Product
node.Description: Description about any article or substance that is manufactured or refined for sale.

node.Title: Maturity
node.Description: degree to which a system, product or component meets needs for reliability under normal operation

node.Title: Availability
node.Description: degree to which a system, product or component is operational and accessible when required for use

node.Title: Fault tolerance
node.Description: degree to which a system, product or component operates as intended despite the presence of hardware or software faults

node.Title: Recoverability
node.Description: degree to which, in the event of an interruption or a failure, a product or system can recover the data directly affected and re-establish the desired state of the system

node.Title: Time behavior
node.Description: degree to which the response and processing times and throughput rates of a product or system, when performing its functions, meet requirements

node.Title: Resource utilization
node.Description: degree to which the amounts and types of resources used by a product or system, when performing its functions, meet requirements

node.Title: Capacity
node.Description: degree to which the maximum limits of a product or system parameter meet requirements

node.Title: Appropriateness recognizability
node.Description: degree to which users can recognize whether a product or system is appropriate for their needs

node.Title: Learnability
node.Description: degree to which a product or system can be used by specified users to achieve specified goals of learning to use the product or system with effectiveness, efficiency, freedom from risk and satisfaction in a specified context of use

node.Title: Operability
node.Description: degree to which a product or system has attributes that make it easy to operate and control

node.Title: User error protection
node.Description: degree to which a system protects users against making errors

node.Title: User interface aesthetics
node.Description: degree to which a user interface enables pleasing and satisfying interaction for the user

node.Title: Accessibility
node.Description: degree to which a product or system can be used by people with the widest range of characteristics and capabilities to achieve a specified goal in a specified context of use

node.Title: Modularity
node.Description: degree to which a system or computer program is composed of discrete components such that a change to one component has minimal impact on other components

node.Title: Reusability
node.Description: degree to which an asset can be used in more than one system, or in building other assets

node.Title: Analyzability
node.Description: degree of effectiveness and efficiency with which it is possible to assess the impact on a product or system of an intended change to one or more of its parts, or to diagnose a product for deficiencies or causes of failures, or to identify parts to be modified

node.Title: Modifiability
node.Description: degree to which a product or system can be effectively and efficiently modified without introducing defects or degrading existing product quality

node.Title: Testability
node.Description: degree of effectiveness and efficiency with which test criteria can be established for a system, product or component and tests can be performed to determine whether those criteria have been met

node.Title: Confidentiality
node.Description: degree to which a product or system ensures that data are accessible only to those authorized to have access

node.Title: Integrity
node.Description: degree to which a system, product or component prevents unauthorized access to, or modification of, computer programs or data

node.Title: Non-repudiation
node.Description: degree to which actions or events can be proven to have taken place, so that the events or actions cannot be repudiated later

node.Title: Accountability
node.Description: degree to which the actions of an entity can be traced uniquely to the entity

node.Title: Authenticity
node.Description: degree to which the identity of a subject or resource can be proved to be the one claimed

node.Title: Co-existence
node.Description: degree to which a product can perform its required functions efficiently while sharing a common environment and resources with other products, without detrimental impact on any other product

node.Title: Interoperability
node.Description: degree to which two or more systems, products or components can exchange information and use the information that has been exchanged

node.Title: Adaptability
node.Description: degree to which a product or system can effectively and efficiently be adapted for different or evolving hardware, software or other operational or usage environments

node.Title: Installability
node.Description: degree of effectiveness and efficiency with which a product or system can be successfully installed and/or uninstalled in a specified environment

node.Title: Replaceability
node.Description: degree to which a product can replace another specified software product for the same purpose in the same environment

node.Title: Organizational structure
node.Description: Description of the organizational structure of the supplier company.

node.Title: Positioning and Strength
node.Description: Description of the position of the supplier company in the market.

node.Title: Reputation
node.Description: Capability of the supplier to perform similar projects based on past experiences and certifications.

node.Title: Services Offered
node.Description: Description of the services offered by the supplier.

node.Title: Support
node.Description: Description of the support mechanisms offered by the supplier.

node.Title: Licensing Schema
node.Description: Description of the COTS component licensing options.

node.Title: Licensing Costs
node.Description: Detail of the costs for the different licensing options

node.Title: Platform Cost
node.Description: Estimation of the cost for the required production platform

node.Title: Implementation Cost
node.Description: Estimation of implementation costs based on similar past experiences.

node.Title: Network Cost
node.Description: Estimation of additional cost for network operation.

node.Title: Stability
node.Description: Attributes of the product that bear on the stability of the product.

node.Title: Ownership
node.Description: Attributes in relation to the intellectual property rights.

node.Title: Deliverables
node.Description: Detail of the out of the box and post implementation deliverables.

node.Title: Parameterization / Customization
node.Description: Attributes in relation to the initial effort required for the product to operate.

node.Title: Guarantees
node.Description: Detail of the guarantees provided over the product.

node.Title: Foreign Key
node.Description: Provides a reference from an entity to anotherone

node.Title: Date/Time Functions
node.Description: Functions for working with data and time

node.Title: Parallel queries
node.Description: The ability to distribute a single query over serveral CPUs

node.Title: Comparison based on RegEx (regular expression)
node.Description: Conditions with regular expressions that can be used e.g. in a WHERE clause

node.Title: Substring
node.Description: Extract the part of a string value based on a RegEx

node.Title: Replace strings
node.Description: Replace values in a string based on a RegEx

node.Title: Partial index
node.Description: Define an index on a subset of entities

node.Title: Descending Index (Sorted/[Single Field] Index)
node.Description: Define an index that is sorted descending

node.Title: Index on expression (Text Indexes)
node.Description: Create an index based on an expression/function

node.Title: Index using a custom function
node.Description: "Create an expression index using a custom function (written in a "SQL" procedural language)""reate an expression index"

node.Title: Index include columns (Compound Index)
node.Description: Define an index on some columns and include other (non-indexed) columns

node.Title: Clustered index (Multikey Index)
node.Description: An index that contains the table data (index and table storage are the same)

node.Title: Duplicate NULL values in unique index
node.Description: The SQL standard requires that a unique index allows multiple 1 values.

node.Title: Data Definition Language (DDL)
node.Description: Data Definition Language (DDL)

node.Title: Data Manipulation Language (DML)
node.Description: Data Manipulation Language (DML)

node.Title: User defined datatype (UDT)
node.Description: Crate UDTs using SQL and use those UDTs as a column's data type

node.Title: Domains
node.Description: A special kind of user defined data type that can also include check constraints, usually based on a base data type

node.Title: Arrays
node.Description: an array type is a data type that is meant to describe a collection of elements

node.Title: Enums
node.Description: De-normalize lookup values by specifying a fixed set of allowed values (a special case of a check constraint)

node.Title: Numbers
node.Description: Any type of nemric data type, including integer, float, double, etc.

node.Title: String
node.Description: String data type

node.Title: BOOLEAN
node.Description: Standard boolean data type as defined by the SQL standard (usable as a column data type)

node.Title: Interval
node.Description: An interval is defined as the difference between two dates and times.

node.Title: TIME
node.Description: A data type that only stores a time

node.Title: DATE
node.Description: A data type that only stores a date (without a time)

node.Title: TIMESTAMP
node.Description: A data type that only stores a date and time

node.Title: Big Binary (Blob)
node.Description: A Binary Large OBject (BLOB) is a collection of binary data stored as a single entity in a database management system. Blobs are typically images, audio or other multimedia objects, though sometimes binary executable code is stored as a blob. Database support for blobs is not universal.

node.Title: Range types
node.Description: A data type that represents a range of values

node.Title: Stored procedure (UDF)
node.Description: Writing and managing stored procedures using SQL commands

node.Title: Statement level triggers
node.Description: Triggers that fire once for each statement

node.Title: Built-in scheduler
node.Description: Scheduled jobs with sessions and batch files as parameters are launched as services running in background. Scheduler allows keeping migration tasks unattended and executes them automatically at specified time or a particular period of time.

node.Title: User defined operators
node.Description: Create new (comparison) operators for user defined data types

node.Title: Custom aggregation
node.Description: Create aggregate functions using SQL

node.Title: Function overloading
node.Description: Create different versions of the same function that are distinguished by their argument list

node.Title: Before triggers
node.Description: Triggers that are fired before the changes of a DML statement are persisted

node.Title: XML
node.Description: The DBMS supports XML API

node.Title: XPath
node.Description: The DBMS supports XPath API

node.Title: XQuery
node.Description: The DBMS supports XQuery API

node.Title: JSON
node.Description: The DBMS supports JSON API

node.Title: Indexes on JSON documents
node.Description: The DBMS supports Indexes on JSON documents

node.Title: ACID (Immediate Consistency)
node.Description: ACID (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) is a set of properties of database transactions.

node.Title: BASE (Eventual Consistency)
node.Description: Eventually consistent services are often classified as providing BASE (Basically Available, Soft state, Eventual consistency) semantics, in contrast to traditional ACID (Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability) guarantees.

node.Title: Concurrent manipulation of data
node.Description: Support multiple access

node.Title: Two-phase locking / commit
node.Description: Controlling access to data by locks assigned to the data. Access of a transaction to a data item (database object) locked by another transaction may be blocked (depending on lock type and access operation type) until lock release.

node.Title: Serialization graph checking
node.Description: (also called Serializability, or Conflict, or Precedence graph checking) - Checking for cycles in the schedule's graph and breaking them by aborts.

node.Title: Timestamp ordering
node.Description: Assigning timestamps to transactions, and controlling or checking access to data by timestamp order.

node.Title: Commitment ordering
node.Description: Controlling or checking transactions' chronological order of commit events to be compatible with their respective precedence order.

node.Title: Index concurrency control
node.Description: Synchronizing access operations to indexes, rather than to user data. Specialized methods provide substantial performance gains.

node.Title: Multiversion concurrency control (MVCC)
node.Description: Each transaction maintains a private workspace for its accessed data, and its changed data become visible outside the transaction only upon its commit. This model provides a different concurrency control behavior with benefits in many cases.

node.Title: Optimistic locking
node.Description: Optimistic Locking is a strategy where you read a record, take note of a version number and check that the version hasn't changed before you write the record back.

node.Title: Range Partitioning
node.Description: Range partitioning is a partitioning technique where ranges of data is stored separately in different sub-tables. MAXVALUE is provided as a catch-all for values that exceed all ranges specified.

node.Title: Hash Partitioning
node.Description: Hash partitioning is a partitioning technique where a hash key is used to distribute rows evenly across the different partitions (sub-tables).

node.Title: Composite partitioning
node.Description: Composite partitioning is a combination of the basic data distribution methods; a table is partitioned by one data distribution method and then each partition is further subdivided into subpartitions using a second data distribution method. All subpartitions for a given partition represent a logical subset of the data.

node.Title: List Partitioning
node.Description: In list partitioning, each partition is defined and selected based on the membership of a column value in one of a set of value lists, rather than in one of a set of contiguous ranges of values.

node.Title: Horizontal partitioning (Sharding)
node.Description: A database shard is a horizontal partition of data in a database. Each individual partition is referred to as a shard or database shard. Each shard is held on a separate database server instance, to spread load.

node.Title: Reference Partitioning
node.Description: Reference partitioning enables the partitioning of two tables that are related to one another by referential constraints. The partitioning key is resolved through an existing parent-child relationship, enforced by enabled and active primary key and foreign key constraints.

node.Title: Interval Partitioning
node.Description: Interval partitioning is an extension of range partitioning, where the system is able to create new partitions as they are required. The PARTITION BY RANGE clause is used in the normal way to identify the transition point for the partition, then the new INTERVALclause used to calculate the range for new partitions when the values go beyond the existing transition point.

node.Title: Interval Reference Partitioning
node.Description: This feature enables reference-partitioned table to use interval partitioning as a top partitioning strategy, which provides a better partitioning modeling. Interval partitioned tables can be used as parent tables for reference partitioning.

node.Title: Statement Auditing
node.Description: Statement auditing audits the use of several types of related actions for each option.

node.Title: Privilege Auditing
node.Description: Audits the use of system privileges that enable corresponding actions. Privilege auditing is more focused than statement auditing, which audits only a particular type of action.

node.Title: Schema Object Auditing
node.Description: Audits specific statements on a particular schema object. Schema object auditing is very focused, auditing only a single specified type of statement (such as SELECT) on a specified schema object.

node.Title: Fine-Grained Auditing
node.Description: Audits, at the most granular level, data access and actions based on content, using any boolean measure, such as value > 1,000,000. Enables auditing based on access to or changes in a column.

node.Title: Account Locking
node.Description: locking out an account due to prevent security threat (multiple password failure)

node.Title: Password Lifetime and Expiration
node.Description: Specify a maximum lifetime for passwords. When the specified amount of time passes and the password expires, the user or DBA must change the password.

node.Title: Password History
node.Description: The Enforce password history policy setting determines the number of unique new passwords that must be associated with a user account before an old password can be reused.

node.Title: Password Complexity Verification
node.Description: Database checks that new or changed passwords are sufficiently complex to prevent intruders who try to break into the system by guessing passwords.

node.Title: Label Based Access Control
node.Description: Label-based access control (LBAC) is automatically enforced by the system; and roles, providing a fine-grained approach to system administration thereby eliminating the need for the super-user function.

node.Title: Role Based Access Control
node.Description: Role-based access control (RBAC) is an approach to restricting system access to authorized users.

node.Title: Row level security
node.Description: Row level security (RLS) enables you to store data for many users in a single database and table, while at the same time restricting row-level access based on a user's identity, role, or execution context.

node.Title: Firewall protection
node.Description: A network security system that controls the incoming and outgoing network traffic based on an applied rule set.

node.Title: Grant on column level
node.Description: Grant access to only some of the columns

node.Title: MapReduce
node.Description: A MapReduce job usually splits the input data-set into independent chunks which are processed by the map tasks in a completely parallel manner.

node.Title: Vertical scalability (Scale up/down)
node.Description: To scale horizontally (or scale out/in) means to add more nodes to (or remove nodes from) a DBMS

node.Title: Horizontal Scalability (Scale out/in)
node.Description: To scale vertically (or scale up/down) means to add resources to (or remove resources from) a single node in a DBMS

node.Title: Native network encryption
node.Description: Native network encryption is the ability to encrypt database connections, without the configuration overhead of TCP/IP and SSL/TLS and without the need to open and listen on different ports.

node.Title: Encrypt Data in Transit/Motion
node.Description: Data-in-motion is encrypted usually using TLS/SSL protocol, so the data is encrypted while is transferred from client to the cloud and is not anymore vulnerable to eavesdropping and tampering, but once it arrives on server, data is decrypted and processed by the database service and then stored.

node.Title: Transparent Data Encryption
node.Description: Data-in-motion is encrypted usually using TLS/SSL protocol, so the data is encrypted while is transferred from client to the cloud and is not anymore vulnerable to eavesdropping and tampering, but once it arrives on server, data is decrypted and processed by the database service and then stored.

node.Title: Field-Level Encryption
node.Description: All values in a field of an entity are encrypted with the same password (word or phrase), the same encryption algorithm, and the same cipher mode.

node.Title: Encrypting File System (EFS)
node.Description: The Encrypting File System (EFS) on Microsoft Windows is a feature introduced in version 3.0 of NTFS that provides filesystem-level encryption. The technology enables files to be transparently encrypted to protect confidential data from attackers with physical access to the computer.

node.Title: Closed database backups
node.Description: When using operating system utilities for closed backups, the backups are done while the database is closed.

node.Title: Open database backups
node.Description: the backups are done while the database is opend. (incosistent backup)

node.Title: Incremental backups
node.Description: An incremental backup is one that provides a backup of files that have changed or are new since the last incremental backup; it is one that backs up only the data that have changed since the last backup — be it a full or incremental backup.

node.Title: Corrupt block detection at backup
node.Description: A detected corrupt block (for example, through a user's SQL query) is now automatically repaired by using a good block from a physical standby database.

node.Title: Media Recovery
node.Description: Datafile media recovery is sometimes alse called media recovery. Datafile media recovery is used to recover from a damaged (or lost) datafile, control file or spfile. The goal of datafile media recovery is to restore database integrity.

node.Title: Crash Recovery
node.Description: Crash recovery is the process by which the database is moved back to a consistent and usable state. This is done by rolling back incomplete transactions and completing committed transactions that were still in memory when the crashoccurred

node.Title: Complete Recovery
node.Description: Recover the whole database, a tablespace, or a datafile.

node.Title: Instance Recovery
node.Description: When instance fails before committed data are written into data files, the DBMS uses the data recorded in the online redo log files to recover the lost data when the associated database is re-started. This process is called Roll forward or cache recovery.

node.Title: Query Optimizer
node.Description: Query optimization is a function of many database management systems. The query optimizer attempts to determine the most efficient way to execute a given query by considering the possible query plans.

node.Title: In-memory capabilities
node.Description: Some/all parts of the DB structure are held in the memory

node.Title: Entity Compression
node.Description: For each entity a value is identified that can be used to reduce the storage space for the values in each entity

node.Title: Prefix compression
node.Description: For each field, a value is identified that can be used to reduce the storage space for the values in each field

node.Title: Dictionary compression
node.Description: Dictionary compression searches for repeated values anywhere on the page, and stores them in the CI area.

node.Title: Unicode Compression
node.Description: The Standard Compression Scheme for Unicode (SCSU) is a Unicode Technical Standard for reducing the number of bytes needed to represent Unicode text, especially if that text uses mostly characters from one or a small number of per-language character blocks.

node.Title: Database as a service (DaaS)
node.Description: A cloud database is a database that typically runs on a cloud computing platform. There are two common deployment models: users can run databases on the cloudindependently, using a virtual machine image, or they can purchase access to a database service, maintained by a cloud database provider.

node.Title: CROSS JOIN
node.Description: The SQL CROSS JOIN produces a result set which is the number of rows in the first table multiplied by the number of rows in the second table if no WHERE clause is used along with CROSS JOIN. This kind of result is called as Cartesian Product. If WHERE clause is used with CROSS JOIN, it functions like an INNER JOIN.

node.Title: FULL OUTER JOIN
node.Description: In SQL the FULL OUTER JOIN combines the results of both left and right outer joins and returns all (matched or unmatched) rows from the tables on both sides of the join clause.

node.Title: LATERAL JOIN
node.Description: Subqueries appearing in FROM can be preceded by the key word LATERAL. This allows them to reference columns provided by preceding FROM items. (Without LATERAL, each subquery is evaluated independently and so cannot cross-reference any other FROM item.)

node.Title: JOIN ... USING
node.Description: A shortcut notation for the JOIN operator when both columns have the same name.

node.Title: JOINs using tuple comparison
node.Description: Use tuples in JOIN conditions

node.Title: INTERSECT
node.Description: Returns any distinct values that are returned by both the query on the left and right sides of the INTERSECT operator.

node.Title: EXCEPT
node.Description: Returns any distinct values from the query to the left of the EXCEPT operator that are not also returned from the right query.

node.Title: ORDER BY ... NULLS LAST
node.Description: The SQL standard does not define the order of rows when 1 values are present in the column on which the result is sorted. To control if 1 values should be sorted before or after non-1 values, 1S FIRST/LAST can be added to an ORDER BY clause

node.Title: IS DISTINCT FROM
node.Description: IS DISTINCT FROM allows a 1 aware comparison to test if two values are different

node.Title: BETWEEN SYMMETRIC
node.Description: By default the the BETWEEN operator requires the lower bound and upper bound to be "in order" will not return anything. When using BETWEEN SYMMETRIC, the order is irrelevant.""y default the the BETWEEN operator requires the lower bound and upper bound to be "in orde"" defaul"

node.Title: OVERLAPS
node.Description: Checks for overlapping intervals

node.Title: Window functions
node.Description: Window functions (introduced in the SQL 2003 standard) allow to calculate grouped values without grouping the overall query: multiple times in a query

node.Title: Common Table Expressions
node.Description: A common table expression very similar to a derived table, only that it can be used multiple times in a query

node.Title: CTE in a sub-query
node.Description: Use a common table expression in a sub-query, not only as a top level query

node.Title: Recursive Queries
node.Description: Recursive queries are used to query hierarchical data. The SQL standard defines a special syntax for common table expressions to enable recursive processing.

node.Title: Row constructor
node.Description: "Use of the VALUES row-constructor wherever a table reference can be used.Sometimes also called "table value constructor"""se of the VALUES row-con"

node.Title: Filtered aggregates
node.Description: Filtered aggregates are used to include only some rows into the aggregation

node.Title: PIVOT Support
node.Description: PIVOT rotates a table-valued expression by turning the unique values from one column in the expression into multiple columns in the output, and performs aggregations where they are required on any remaining column values that are wanted in the final output.

node.Title: GROUP BY .. ROLLUP
node.Description: The ROLLUP, CUBE, or GROUPING SETS operators can generate the same result set as when you use UNION ALL to combine single grouping queries;

node.Title: Temporal queries
node.Description: Temporal queries allow querying the database (or a single table) to return the data as it was in the past

node.Title: SELECT without a FROM clause
node.Description: A SELECT that returns one (or more) constant values without a FROM clause.

node.Title: Aggregates for strings
node.Description: Aggregate multiple string values to a single value, optionally delimited.

node.Title: Tuple comparison
node.Description: The ability to compare multiple columns (tuples) the same way a single column can be compared

node.Title: Tuple updates
node.Description: The ability to update multiple columns (tuples) with a single SET operator

node.Title: UPDATE with a join
node.Description: The ability to JOIN multiple tables when using UPDATE

node.Title: Query variables
node.Description: Variables that can be used inside a single query without the need to use procedural code

node.Title: Deferred constraints
node.Description: By default foreign key constraints are evaluated when the DML statement is executed. When a constraint is deferred, it is checked only when the transaction is committed.

node.Title: Check constraints
node.Description: Simple check constraint

node.Title: Check constraints with sub-query
node.Description: Check constraint using a sub-select

node.Title: Check constraints using custom functions
node.Description: Create a check constraint that is based on the return value of a user-defined function

node.Title: Exclusion constraints
node.Description: Constraints that prevent e.g. overlapping ranges

node.Title: Referential integrity
node.Description: Referential integrity is a property of data which, when satisfied, requires every value of one attribute (column) of a relation (table) to exist as a value of another attribute (column) in a different (or the same) relation (table)

node.Title: Writeable CTEs
node.Description: A common table expression that uses one ore more DML statements

node.Title: Multi-row INSERTs (Bulk import)
node.Description: Insert more than one row with a single INSERT statement

node.Title: TRUNCATE table with FK
node.Description: Truncate tables that are referenced by other tables

node.Title: Read consistency during DML operations
node.Description: During a DML operation reading a column value should return the value that was valid before the statement started

node.Title: Use target table in sub-queries
node.Description: Use the targe table of an UPDATE, DELETE or INSERT statement in a sub-select

node.Title: MERGE support
node.Description: "Update rows if they exist, insert if not (sometimes also named "UPSERT")""pdate ro"

node.Title: SELECT .. FOR UPDATE NOWAIT
node.Description: Select one (or more) rows and lock them for a future update. Fail with an error if the lock cannot be obtained

node.Title: RETURNING clause as a result set
node.Description: The ability to return the modified/deleted/inserted rows from a DML statement as a regular result set

node.Title: Multi-version Insert (data Versioning)
node.Description: Versioning refers to saving new copies of data when you make changes so that you can go back and retrieve specific versions of it later.

node.Title: Parallel DML
node.Description: Ability to execute parallel DML

node.Title: Transactional DDL
node.Description: The ability to rollback any DDL statement

node.Title: Computed columns
node.Description: Define a column in a table that is always calculated based on other columns

node.Title: Functions as column default
node.Description: Use any function (including user defined functions) as the default for a column

node.Title: Sequences
node.Description: Sequences allow for automatic generation of sequential non-repeating or repeating integer values for use in keys or elsewhere. Sequences can be positive or negative. Also a number of values can be cached for performance. However, in the case of a database shut down these cached values are lost. If a statement that references a sequence is rolled back that sequence number will be lost.

node.Title: Auto increment columns
node.Description: Columns that are populated automatically with unique values without the usage of triggers

node.Title: Synonyms
node.Description: A synonym is an alternative name for objects such as tables, views, sequences, stored procedures, and other database objects. You generally use synonyms when you are granting access to an object from another schema and you don't want the users to have to worry about knowing which schema owns the object.

node.Title: Non-blocking index creation
node.Description: Create an index without blocking DML on the table

node.Title: Partitioning
node.Description: After defining partitions, DDL statements can access and manipulate individuals partitions rather than entire tables or indexes. This is how partitioning can simplify the manageability of large database objects. Also, partitioning is entirely transparent to applications.

node.Title: Cascading DROP
node.Description: Drop a table including incoming foreign keys

node.Title: DDL Triggers
node.Description: Define triggers that are fired when a DDL statement is executed

node.Title: TRUNCATE Trigger
node.Description: Define triggers that are fired when a TRUNCATE statement is executed

node.Title: Custom name for PK constraint
node.Description: Specify the name of the PK constraint

node.Title: ALTER a table used in a view
node.Description: The ability to ALTER the definition of a table used in a view without dropping the view

node.Title: Materialized views
node.Description: Persist the result of a query as a table

node.Title: MVIEW with query rewrite
node.Description: If applicable can the optimizer detect that a query against the base tables can be done using the materialized view

node.Title: Automatically updated MVIEWS
node.Description: MVIEW is automatically updated when the underlying tables are changed

node.Title: Permanent global temporary tables
node.Description: Tmporary tables that are created once and that need to be dropped manualy (their definition is retained across server restarts)

node.Title: Global temporary tables
node.Description: Temporary tables that are always visible, but the data is session specific

node.Title: Session local temporary tables
node.Description: Temporary tables that are automatically dropped at the end of the transaction or when the session is disconnected

node.Title: Use a temporary table twice in a single query
node.Description: Use a temporary table twice in a single query

node.Title: Updateable Views
node.Description: Some views are updatable and references to them can be used to specify tables to be updated in data change statements. That is, you can use them in statements such as UPDATE, DELETE, or INSERT to update the contents of the underlying table. Derived tables can also be specified in multiple-table UPDATE and DELETE statements, but can only be used for reading data to specify rows to be updated or deleted. Generally, the view references must be updatable, meaning that they may be merged and not materialized. Composite views have more complex rules.

node.Title: WITH CHECK OPTION
node.Description: Create updateable views where only rows can be updated/deleted/inserted that match the WHERE clause of the view

node.Title: Triggers on views
node.Description: On views, triggers can be defined to execute instead of INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE operations. INSTEAD OF triggers are fired once for each row that needs to be modified in the view. It is the responsibility of the trigger's function to perform the necessary modifications to the underlying base tables and, where appropriate, return the modified row as it will appear in the view. Triggers on views can also be defined to execute once per SQL statement, before or after INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE operations.

node.Title: Views with derived tables
node.Description: Create a view that uses a derived table

node.Title: Table functions
node.Description: Functions that return result sets and can be used like a table

node.Title: Row level triggers
node.Description: Triggers that fire once for each row

node.Title: Dynamic SQL in functions
node.Description: The ability to use dynamic SQL in stored functions

node.Title: Dynamic SQL in triggers
node.Description: The ability to use dynamic SQL in triggers

node.Title: Delete triggers fired by cascading deletes
node.Description: When rows are deleted due to a ON DELETE CASCADE foreign key, are delete triggers fired?

node.Title: Open Source License
node.Description: Open source licenses are licenses that comply with the Open Source Definition — in brief, they allow software to be freely used, modified, and shared. To be approved by the Open Source Initiative (also known as the OSI), a license must go through the Open Source Initiative's license review process.

node.Title: Pricing Model
node.Description: A pricing model is a method used by a company to determine the prices for its products or services. A company must consider factors such as the positioning of its products and services as well as production costs when setting the prices of its goods and services.

node.Title: Popularity in the market
node.Description: db-engines.com ranking

node.Title: Relational
node.Description: This model organizes data into one or more tables (or "relations") of columns and rows, with a unique key identifying each row. Rows are also called records or tuples. Generally, each table/relation represents one "entity type". The rows represent instances of that type of entity and the columns representing values attributed to that instance.

node.Title: Key-value
node.Description: A key-value store, or key-value database, is a data storage model designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a dictionary or hash. Dictionaries contain a collection of objects, or records, which in turn have many different fields within them, each containing data. These records are stored and retrieved using a key that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to quickly find the data within the database.

node.Title: Document
node.Description: Document-oriented databases are inherently a subclass of the key-value store. The central concept of a document-oriented database is the notion of a document. While each document-oriented database implementation differs on the details of this definition, in general, they all assume documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings. Encodings in use include XML, YAML, JSON, and BSON, as well as binary forms like PDF and Microsoft Office documents (MS Word, Excel, and so on).

node.Title: Graph
node.Description: A graph database is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges and properties to represent and store data. The edges allow data in the store to be linked together directly, and in most cases retrieved with a single operation. This contrasts with conventional relational databases, where links between data are stored in the data itself, and queries search for this data within the store and use the JOIN concept to collect the related data.

node.Title: Event Stores
node.Description: Event sourcing is a way of persisting of an application's state by storing the history that determines the current state of the application. This model stores all the changes (events) to the system, rather than just its current state, and returns the stream of events associated with an aggregate instance so that one can replay the events to recreate the state of the aggregate.

node.Title: Object oriented
node.Description: An object database (OODBMS) allows object-oriented programmers to develop the product, store them as objects, and replicate or modify existing objects to make new objects within the OODBMS. Because the database is integrated with the programming language, the programmer can maintain consistency within one environment, in that both the OODBMS and the programming language will use the same model of representation. Relational DBMS projects, by way of contrast, maintain a clearer division between the database model and the application.

node.Title: Multi-value
node.Description: These databases differ from a relational database in that they have features that support and encourage the use of attributes which can take a list of values, rather than all attributes being single-valued.

node.Title: Native XML
node.Description: An XML database is a data persistence software system that allows data to be specified, and sometimes stored, in XML format. These data can be queried, transformed, exported and returned to a calling system. XML databases are a flavor of document-oriented databases.

node.Title: Wide column
node.Description: A wide column store is a type of key-value database. It uses tables, rows, and columns, but unlike a relational database, the names and format of the columns can vary from row to row in the same table.

node.Title: Content store
node.Description: The content store is optionally used to store large binary values. Normally all node and property data is stored in a persistence manager, but for large binaries such as files special treatment can improve performance and reduce disk usage.

node.Title: Add table column at specific position
node.Description: Add a column at specific position in a table.

node.Title: Compression
node.Description: Compression is a reduction in the number of bits needed to represent data. Compressing data can save storage capacity, speed file transfer, and decrease costs for storage hardware and network bandwidth.

node.Title: Cardinality/Relationship
node.Description: The degree of relationship (also known as cardinality) is the number of occurrences in one entity which are associated (or linked) to the number of occurrences in another. There are three degrees of relationship, known as: one-to-one (1:1) one-to-many (1:M)

node.Title: Supported Platform
node.Description: Operating System/Platform

node.Title: Supported Driver (PL)
node.Description: Drivers are a software component enabling an application to interact with a database. They are designed to work with a specific programming language.

node.Title: Join Statements
node.Description: Join (SQL) A SQL join clause combines columns from one or more tables in a relational database. It creates a set that can be saved as a table or used as it is. A JOIN is a means for combining columns from one (self-table) or more tables by using values common to each.

node.Title: Constraints
node.Description: Constraints in DBMS. Constraints enforce limits to the data or type of data that can be inserted/updated/deleted from a table. The whole purpose of constraints is to maintain the data integrity during an update/delete/insert into a table.

node.Title: String Functions
node.Description: String functions are functions that have a non-numerical result. A string is a sequence of characters not interpreted as a number.

node.Title: Query Statements
node.Description: These statements are used to perform tasks such as update data on a database, or retrieve data from a database.

node.Title: Secondary Indexing
node.Description: A secondary index is a data structure that contains a subset of attributes from a table, along with an alternate key to support Query operations. You can retrieve data from the index using a Query , in much the same way as you use Query with a table.

node.Title: Data Types
node.Description: A data type or simply type is a classification of data which tells the compiler or interpreter how the programmer intends to use the data. Most programming languages support various types of data, for example: real, integer or Boolean. A Data type provides a set of values from which an expression (i.e. variable, function ...) may take its values. The type defines the operations that can be done on the data, the meaning of the data, and the way values of that type can be stored.

node.Title: NoSQL Features
node.Description: A NoSQL (originally referring to "non SQL", "non relational" or "not only SQL") database provides a mechanism for storage and retrieval of data which is modeled in means other than the tabular relations used in relational databases.

node.Title: Locking and Concurrency Control
node.Description: Concurrency control is a database management systems (DBMS) concept that is used to address conflicts with the simultaneous accessing or altering of data that can occur with a multi-user system.

node.Title: Auditing
node.Description: Database auditing involves observing a database so as to be aware of the actions of database users. Database administrators and consultants often set up auditing for security purposes, for example, to ensure that those without the permission to access information do not access it.

node.Title: Password Management
node.Description: It helps a user store and organize passwords.

node.Title: Access Control
node.Description: Access control systems perform authorization identification, authentication, access approval, and accountability of entities through login credentials including passwords, personal identification numbers (PINs), biometric scans, and physical or electronic keys.

node.Title: Scalability
node.Description: Scalability is a characteristic of a system, model or function that describes its capability to cope and perform under an increased or expanding workload. A system that scales well will be able to maintain or even increase its level of performance or efficiency when tested by larger operational demands.

node.Title: Views
node.Description: A database view is a searchable object in a database that is defined by a query. Though a view doesn't store data, some refer to a views as “virtual tables,” you can query a view like you can a table. A view can combine data from two or more table, using joins, and also just contain a subset of information.

node.Title: Temporary Tables
node.Description: SQL Server provides the concept of temporary table which helps the developer in a great way. These tables can be created at runtime and can do the all kinds of operations that one normal table can do. But, based on the table types, the scope is limited. These tables are created inside tempdb database.

node.Title: Data storage model
node.Description: Data Models are fundamental entities to introduce abstraction in a DBMS. Data models define how data is connected to each other and how they are processed and stored inside the system. The very first data model could be flat data-models, where all the data used are to be kept in the same plane.

node.Title: Encryption
node.Description: Data encryption translates data into another form, or code, so that only people with access to a secret key (formally called a decryption key) or password can read it. Encrypted data is commonly referred to as ciphertext, while unencrypted data is called plaintext.

node.Title: Backup
node.Description: A backup is a copy of data from your database that can be used to reconstruct that data. Backups can be divided into physical backups and logical backups. Physical backups are backups of the physical files used in storing and recovering your database, such as datafiles, control files, and archived redo logs.

node.Title: Recovery
node.Description: The recovery system ensures the database contains exactly those updates produced by committed transactions.

node.Title: Database Operations
node.Description: The simple operations related to a DBMS, such as modifying a database, etc.

node.Title: Transaction/Consistency
node.Description: Consistency in database systems refers to the requirement that any given database transaction must change affected data only in allowed ways. Any data written to the database must be valid according to all defined rules, including constraints, cascades, triggers, and any combination thereof.

node.Title: Partitioning method
node.Description: Partitioning is the database process where very large tables are divided into multiple smaller parts. By splitting a large table into smaller, individual tables, queries that access only a fraction of the data can run faster because there is less data to scan.

node.Title: Collation
node.Description: Collations provide sorting rules, case, and accent sensitivity properties for your data. Collations that are used with character data types such as char and varchar dictate the code page and corresponding characters that can be represented for that data type.

node.Title: Paging
node.Description: Paging is a method of writing data to, and reading it from, secondary storage for use in primary storage, also known as main memory. Paging plays a role in memory management for a computer's operating system.

node.Title: Replication
node.Description: Database replication is the frequent electronic copying data from a database in one computer or server to a database in another so that all users share the same level of information. The result is a distributed database in which users can access data relevant to their tasks without interfering with the work of others.

node.Title: Snapshot Replication
node.Description: Snapshot replication refers to a replication method between databases. During this process, data is infrequently updated at specified times by copying data changes from the original database (publisher) to a receiving database (subscriber).

node.Title: Transactional Replication
node.Description: Transactional replication typically starts with a snapshot of the publication database objects and data. As soon as the initial snapshot is taken, subsequent data changes and schema modifications made at the Publisher are usually delivered to the Subscriber as they occur (in near real time).

node.Title: Merge Replication
node.Description: Merge replication, like transactional replication, typically starts with a snapshot of the publication database objects and data. Subsequent data changes and schema modifications made at the Publisher and Subscribers are tracked with triggers. The Subscriber synchronizes with the Publisher when connected to the network and exchanges all rows that have changed between the Publisher and Subscriber since the last time synchronization occurred.
